<TITLE> Kuwait may deport 4000 Bangladeshis </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sept 30 (bdnews24.com)--Kuwait may deport 4,000 Bangladeshis who are reportedly guilty of overstaying or allegedly involved in illegal activities, media reports say. Kuwait Times reported on Sep 28 that the Kuwait home ministry has taken the decision. About 1,000 Bangladeshis were deported from Kuwait following violent protests over poor pay and work conditions in 2008. The news report said a total of 17,000 expatriate workers will fall under the deportation plan. Besides the Bangladeshis, 3,500 Indians, 1,000 Pakistanis, 1,200 Egyptians, 1,000 Filipinos, 1,000 Indonesians, 750 Syrians, 500 Thais, 500 Iranians, 1,000 Afghans and 500 Nepalese would be sent back. Meanwhile, Dubai-based Gulf News also reported that the workers would be deported since most of them have do not have a specific job. Currently, there are around 4,00,000 Bangladeshi workers in Kuwait, but it stopped hiring from Bangladesh in late 2006, citing irregularities in the recruitment process. b
